PART 1 — PRIVATE KEY SECURITY
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

RULE: Private keys are NEVER stored in:
  ✗ Source code
  ✗ Git repository (even private)
  ✗ Environment variables on the production server
  ✗ Log files
  ✗ RAM (outside of the TEE enclave process)

APPROVED key storage:
  ✓ AWS Nitro Enclave (primary — see INFRASTRUCTURE_SETUP_GUIDE Step 7)
  ✓ AWS KMS (fallback for less latency-sensitive operations)

Wallet architecture:
  Funder Wallet:   Holds all USDC capital. Never used for signing.
                   Only approve allowances from this wallet. Cold storage.
  Signer Wallet:   The "proxy" key stored in Nitro Enclave.
                   Signs all EIP-712 orders. Zero USDC balance itself.
  API Key Wallet:  Derived from signer wallet. Used only for REST auth headers.

If the signer key is ever compromised:
  1. Immediately revoke allowances from funder wallet
  2. Transfer USDC to a fresh wallet
  3. Generate new signer key in a fresh enclave
  This process should take < 5 minutes. Practice it in staging.

